@Node "Introduction" "Introduction to AMF"

	@{B}@{U}Introduction to AMF@{UB}@{UU}

  AMF was born as a file manager for the Amiga, but while developing the core of the program, I felt 
the need to build a more powerful program that wasn't just a simple tool focused on file 
administration, but could be an administrator of many resources.

  At first, I want to explain why I have taken the decision to expand my original project. When I started 
to develop software, I wanted to build a program to simplify working with the Amiga. The Amiga is a 
great computer, but the workbench is quite old. So I wanted a program that would be faster for 
browsing drawers, to start applications and with more flexible association between data files and their 
own applications. Only by merging these features could I build a useful tool for all Amiga users. But 
that marked the start of my problems because immediately I encountered a big obstacle: 
communication with other programs. Just an example: I want to display a JPEG (or GIF, IFF, etc.) file 
with my favourite viewer. All that I need is to launch the program by passing the file as an argument. 
Well, what happens, if now, I double click on another jpeg file? My program will start another session 
of the viewer. Not too bad, you think, but that can be a problem. First, of memory,because with big 
programs like photo editors two or more sessions can be too much for your Amiga. Secondly, 
because some programs are not capable of starting more than one session, so you should be forced 
to close the program before you double click on another file which you want to work with. Probably 
You are now thinking that I should solve this problem with ARexx, but not all programs have an 
ARexx interface and, above all, I cannot spend my time finding out how those ARexx interfaces work. 
Of course I could pop up a requester in which users can put the ARexx command to load athe file (s) 
with their favourite programs, so that with a double click you load a new file instead of launching a 
new session, but this is not my idea of @{B}user friendly@{UB}. (How many people know anything 
about ARexx programming?).

  So here is my solution: an open structure in which programs can plug-in receiving a set of 
instructions to communicate with the main program and the other plug-ins too. This moves the 
problem onto the programmers, who need to know how to interface their programs with the main and 
the other ones, instead of users. But programmers are the people from which users expect problems 
will be solved.

@EndNode

@Node "MainPage" "Main Page of AMF"

	@{B}@{U}The Main Page@{UB}@{UU}

  The Main Page of AMF contains a row of buttons and two lists: a tree of directories and a list of files.

  The @{" Buttons " Link "Buttons"} are used to accomplish most of the AMF functions, like copy, 
move, delete, rename files. Some functions can be accomplished also with @{" Drag & Drop " Link "DragDrop"}. 
Some buttons are shaded when they aren't of any use (when you have not selected any files at all).

  The @{B}Tree List@{UB} shows the directory tree of the chosen volumes. You can add volumes 
not listed with the @{" Pop Up " Link "Buttons" 7} button and you can choose which volumes will be 
listed at every program startup with @{" preferences " Link "PrefPage"}.

  The @{B}File List@{UB} shows sub directories and files of the selected directory in the Tree List. 
You can select files and/or directories to perform many operations on them (rename, copy, move, 
delete) either with buttons or with Drag & Drop.

@EndNode

@Node "Buttons" "The function buttons"

	@{B}@{U}Buttons@{UB}@{UU}

  The two first buttons to the left, act on the tree list, the next one on the other lists and the other ones 
on the file list.

  The @{B}Pop Up@{UB} button opens a volumes list, from which you can choose volumes to add to 
the tree list. You can also manually type the name of a volume in the associated string and this will 
be added to the tree list, if possible, when you hit the return key (accepting what you have just typed). 
This button acts on the tree list.

  The @{B}Show/Hide@{UB} button turn on/off the tree list. This button acts on the tree list.

  The @{B}New Drawer@{UB} button opens a window in which you can enter a name for a new 
directory. This new directory will be added to the current dir. @{B}Bugs:@{UB} actually you cannot 
close this window with close requester (to abort operation) but you need to hit enter with empty string 
field to do so. This button acts on the tree list and file list.

  The @{B}Rename@{UB} button opens a window to edit the name of the current active entry in file 
list. If you have a multiselection when you press this button, only the active entry will be editable. 
@{B}Bugs:@{UB} as New Drawer button, but here you can close the window hitting the enter key 
without modification on the file name. This button acts on the file list.

  The @{B}Cut@{UB} button clears the current selection and buffers it to perform a move operation, 
highligthing the button to help you remember you have a selection buffered. To change the selection 
you need to press the button again (it turns to normal state) and select new files/dirs. If you press this 
button with the copy button highlighted you mantain the previous selection ,but, are ready for a move 
operation. This button acts on the file list.

  The @{B}Copy@{UB} button clears the current selection and buffers it to perform a copy operation, 
highligthing the button to help you remember you have a selection buffered. To change the selection 
you need to press the button again (it turns to normal state) and to select new files/dirs. If you press 
this button with the move button highlighted you mantain the previous selection, but, are ready for a 
copy operation. This button acts on the file list.

  The @{B}Paste@{UB} button performs the current buffered operation (highlighted button). This 
button acts on the file list.

  The @{B}Delete@{UB} button moves the selected files/dirs into a special trashcan. This trashcan is 
a subdir of the AMF drawer named TrashAMF, but you will never see it listed in any list: you can 
access it from my program only with the trash button (see below). This button acts on the file list.

  The @{B}Undo@{UB} button undo the previously made operation.

  The @{B}Trash@{UB} button switches the main window to @{" trash " Link "TrashPage"} window.

  The @{B}Preferences@{UB} button switches the main window to @{" preferences " Link "PrefPage"} window.

@EndNode

@Node "PrefPage" "Preferences Page"

	@{B}@{U}Preferences Page@{UB}@{UU}

  The preferences page is split into two sections: AMF Settings and Data Types Settings.

  The @{B}AMF Settings@{UB} section is again split into two sections: one about multiselection and 
one about Volumes in the tree list.

  The @{B}Multiselection@{UB} section let you to choose between MUI settings and a special AMF 
multiselction. The special AMF multiselection rules are the next ones:

  -  you switch an entry state to selected/unselected clicking on it @{B}holding@{UB} down shift key 	  
     (if an entry is unselected you select it and viceversa);

  -  if you select an entry in the list @{B}without@{UB} holding down shift key the state of entry            
     doesn't change;

  -  when you drag from the list, you drag @{B}only@{UB} selected entries (active entry, if not              
     selected as outlined before, will be not dragged).

This multiselection way is slower but more accurate than MUI one. This setting take effect 
immediately if you press Save or Use button.

  The @{B}Volumes Settings@{UB} section let you chose the volumes to show in the tree list at 
program startup. There is a list with all mounted volumes (updated every time you access 
preferences page) from which you can choose volume names (selecting one of them and clicking on 
@{B}Add@{UB} button). The next list shows the volumes you choose and which will be added 
automatically to the list tree each time the program is started. Changes to these settings take effect 
only at next program start and only if you press the Save button.

  The @{B}Data Types@{UB} Section let you modify or delete actions related to data file double 
clicking. When you select an entry you have the chance to edit its fields. To know how new entries 
are added see @{" Data Type " Link "DataType"}

@EndNode

@Node "DataType" "Data Type"

	@{B}@{U}Data Type@{UB}@{UU}

  In this version you can open data files simply by double clicking on them through data type 
recognition. Every time you double click on a data file in which a data type is not yet registered, you 
are prompted to choose a program to associate with this data type. Next time you double click on a 
file of this data type the choosen program will be started without any prompt. This is quite like the 
way plug-ins work in Internet Browsers.

  In the present version this procedure has been built in a very simple format, so lha archives are of 
binary data type as are programs, for example, because i have used only the datatype.library of 
AmigaOS. In future versions, I planned to introduce a more sophisticated data type recognition, with 
which will be possible to distinguish files of same data type through their extensions and protection 
bits (for example you can choose to open ASCII .doc files with your word processor, ASCII .txt files 
with Multiview and execute ASCII script files).

@EndNode

@Node "DragDrop" "Drag & Drop"

	@{B}@{U}Drag & Drop@{UB}@{UU}

  AMF supports two drag&drop: drag from dirlist (right list) with drop onto tree list (left list) and 
drag&drop within tree list.

  In the first case you can drag a multiselection or a single file/directory and drop it onto an entry of 
the tree list (you will see the current destination in bold; if no entry in the tree list is shown in bold 
when you drop your selection nothing happens). After you drop a selection, it pops up a window with 
which you can choose to move or copy selected files in chosen destination, or abort the operation.

  In the second case you @{B}must@{UB} hold down the shift key (right or left) before you start 
dragging. You can drag just a single entry, anyway subdirs will be moved or copied too. After you 
drop, it pops up a window like the previous case.

@EndNode

@Node "TrashPage" "TrashcanPag Type"

	@{B}@{U}Trashcan Page@{UU}@{UB}

  Trashcan page contains three buttons and a list.

  The first button, left side, will bring you back to the main AMF page.

  The second button restores files and/or directories selected from the list down below into their 
original positions.

  The third button deletes files and/or directories selected from the list down below permanently.

  The preceding operations cannot be performed on subdirs of listed directories, so if you previously 
deleted a directory "abc" which has a subdir "xyz" you have no way to restore or delete only "xyz", 
that will not be showed in the list anyway. Of course this applies to files in the deleted directories too. 
The only way to restore (or to delete) a single member (subdir or file) of a directory is to restore the 
whole directory, move the element in an other position (or delete it, if your intention was to delete) 
and delete again the directory.

  The list shows the files and directories stored in the trashcan. This list is quite like that in the main 
AMF page, but it shows also the original path of each of the entries. If you choose to restore a file or 
a directory, it will be moved into that location (for example "xyz" file with path"System:abc" will be 
restored as "System:abc/xyz").

@EndNode

@Node "Plugin" "Internal Plug-in"

	@{B}@{U}Internal Plug-in@{UB}@{UU}

  To learn about the Internal Plug-in background read @{" introduction " Link "Introduction"} section.

  Here I want to give you some technical words about how they should have to work, but remember 
that internal plug-ins are not enabled in this version because i'm still developing them. @{B}N.B.: this 
document is just an introduction to my future work, so don't rely on it to develop your software, but 
wait for the ultimate version (plug-ins are scheduled for version 1.0 of AMF).@{UB}

  Internal plug-ins are stand alone programs compiled as MUI Custom Class so they can be loaded 
and started from my program as MUI Objects. (If you are not a programmer likely you'll be a little 
confused; don't panic, simply skip this section). To work they need to perform every action by the 
way of methods (that is the way in which all good programs are expected to work).

  A plug-in will be started with NewObject(plug_in, TAG_DONE) where plug_in is a STRPTR to its 
library name (for example, if your plug-in name is "xyz", the variable plug_in need to point to the 
string "xyz.mcc") and added to AMF with the command DoMethod and MethodID OM_ADDMEMBER. 
So you need to inform AMF (by the way of a config file) how your plug-in has to be inserted into the 
application (that is, if it has its own window or not, and, when it hasn't its own window, if it needs AMF 
to reserve a page for it in the main window) and that's all done. Of course your plug-in will receive a 
lot of information (in the form of a message) and if you need to you can use those environmental 
informations to perform astonishing functions... 

  Now the good news (likely you already understand it). If you developed a MUI program, you don't 
have to re-write it in order to build an AMF plug-in. Simply, you need to change your main routine, 
write a dispatcher (in many cases just a few C Language lines) and re-compile your program as a 
library. To know more about MUI Custom Class refer to developer documentations shipped with MUI.

@EndNode

